On a typical 64-bit platform, what does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::cout << sizeof(char) << "\n";
    std::cout << sizeof(int)  << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

A programmer wants to compute how many bits an `int` holds and writes this code. What is the bug?

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    std::cout << sizeof(int) << " bits\n";
    return 0;
}
```

What does this program print? (Assume a typical 64-bit platform.)

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int a{10};
    int b{20};
    std::cout << sizeof(a + b) << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```
